public class InterphaseSlugFlow extends InterphaseTwoPhasePipeFlow implements ThermodynamicConstantsInterface

InterphaseSlugFlow class.

Calculates interphase transport coefficients for slug flow regime. Slug flow is characterized by alternating liquid slugs and gas bubbles (Taylor bubbles) moving through the pipe. This regime is common in horizontal and near-horizontal pipes at intermediate gas and liquid flow rates.

The correlations implemented here are based on the work of:

  • Dukler, A.E. and Hubbard, M.G. (1975) - Slug flow model
  • Andreussi, P. and Bendiksen, K.H. (1989) - Slug characteristics

    • calcSherwoodNumber

      public double calcSherwoodNumber(int phaseNum, double reynoldsNumber, double schmidtNumber, FlowNodeInterface node)

      Calculates the Sherwood number for interphase mass transfer. The Sherwood number is the dimensionless mass transfer coefficient: Sh = k_L * L / D where k_L is the mass transfer coefficient, L is the characteristic length, and D is the diffusivity.

      For slug flow, the Sherwood number is a weighted average of contributions from:

      • Taylor bubble region: Film-like mass transfer (Hewitt correlation)
      • Slug body: Enhanced pipe flow mass transfer with mixing
      • Slug front/back: Enhanced transfer at mixing zones

      Reference: Fernandes et al. (1983), "Hydrodynamic model for gas-liquid slug flow"

      Overrides:
      calcSherwoodNumber in class InterphaseTwoPhasePipeFlow
      Parameters:
      phaseNum - the phase number (0 for gas, 1 for liquid)
      reynoldsNumber - the Reynolds number
      schmidtNumber - the Schmidt number (μ/ρD)
      node - the flow node
      Returns:
      the Sherwood number
